title: Usage
text: input ggoncoplot data.frame 1 row per mutation. data.frame must contain columns describing following: Gene Symbol Sample Identifier (optional) mutation type (optional) tooltip (character string: show mouse hover particular mutation) columns can order, named anything. define mapping input dataset columns required features call ggoncoplot

title: Usage
code: # TCGA GBM dataset from TCGAmuations package gbm_csv <- system.file(package='ggoncoplot', "testdata/GBM_tcgamutations_mc3_maf.csv.gz") gbm_df <- read.csv(file = gbm_csv, header=TRUE)  gbm_df |>    ggoncoplot(     col_genes = 'Hugo_Symbol',      col_samples = 'Tumor_Sample_Barcode'   )

title: Usage
text: Colour mutation specifying col_mutation_type
code: # TCGA GBM dataset from TCGAmuations package gbm_csv <- system.file(package='ggoncoplot', "testdata/GBM_tcgamutations_mc3_maf.csv.gz") gbm_df <- read.csv(file = gbm_csv, header=TRUE)  gbm_df |>    ggoncoplot(     col_genes = 'Hugo_Symbol',      col_samples = 'Tumor_Sample_Barcode',      col_mutation_type = 'Variant_Classification'   )

title: Usage
text: Show 4 frequently mutated genes using topn argument
code: gbm_df |>    ggoncoplot(     col_genes = 'Hugo_Symbol',      col_samples = 'Tumor_Sample_Barcode',      col_mutation_type = 'Variant_Classification',      topn = 4   )

title: Usage
text: lets show TP53 TERT
code: gbm_df |>    ggoncoplot(     col_genes = 'Hugo_Symbol',      col_samples = 'Tumor_Sample_Barcode',      col_mutation_type = 'Variant_Classification',      genes_to_include = c('TP53', 'TERT'),   )

title: Usage
text:
Lets add custom tooltip describes specific mutation Note tooltips html, want insert break, just paste
. Similarly, want make text tooltip bold, try "text_to_bold<\b>"
code: gbm_df |>    mutate(tooltip = paste0(Reference_Allele, ">", Tumor_Seq_Allele2)) |>   ggoncoplot(     col_genes = 'Hugo_Symbol',      col_samples = 'Tumor_Sample_Barcode',      col_mutation_type = 'Variant_Classification',      col_tooltip = 'tooltip' # We'll specify a custom tooltip based on our new 'tooltip' column   )

title: Usage
code: gbm_df |>    ggoncoplot(     col_genes = 'Hugo_Symbol',      col_samples = 'Tumor_Sample_Barcode',      col_mutation_type = 'Variant_Classification',      interactive = FALSE   )

title: Easily Create Interactive Oncoplots
text: input ggoncoplot data.frame 1 row per mutation cohort columns describing following: Gene Symbol Sample Identifier (optional) mutation type (optional) tooltip (character string: show mouse hover particular mutation) columns can order, named anything. define mapping input dataset columns required features call ggoncoplot
code: library(ggoncoplot)  # TCGA GBM dataset from TCGAmuations package gbm_csv <- system.file(package='ggoncoplot', "testdata/GBM_tcgamutations_mc3_maf.csv.gz") gbm_df <- read.csv(file = gbm_csv, header=TRUE)  gbm_df |>    ggoncoplot(     col_genes = 'Hugo_Symbol',      col_samples = 'Tumor_Sample_Barcode',      col_mutation_type = 'Variant_Classification',      topn = 10,      interactive = FALSE   )

title: GG oncoplot — ggoncoplot
code: ggoncoplot(   .data,   col_genes,   col_samples,   col_mutation_type = NULL,   genes_to_include = NULL,   col_tooltip = col_samples,   topn = 10,   show_sample_ids = FALSE,   interactive = TRUE,   interactive_svg_width = 12,   interactive_svg_height = 6,   xlab_title = "Sample",   ylab_title = "Gene" )

title: GG oncoplot — ggoncoplot
text: .data data oncoplot. data.frame 1 row per mutation cohort. Must contain columns describing gene_symbols sample_identifiers, (data.frame) col_genes name data column containing gene names/symbols (string) col_samples name data column containing sample identifiers (string) col_mutation_type name data column describing mutation types (string) genes_to_include specific genes include oncoplot (character) col_tooltip name data column containing whatever information want display (string) topn many top genes visualise. Ignored genes_to_include supplied (number) show_sample_ids show sample_ids_on_x_axis (flag) interactive plot interactive (boolean) interactive_svg_width dimensions interactive plot (number) interactive_svg_height dimensions interactive plot (number) xlab_title x axis lable (string) ylab_title y axis interactive plot (number)

title: GG oncoplot — ggoncoplot
text: ggplot girafe object interactive=TRUE

title: Generate score based on genes — score_based_on_gene_rank
text: Score used sort samples based genes mutated. Make sure run one sample (use grouping)

title: Generate score based on genes — score_based_on_gene_rank
code: score_based_on_gene_rank(   mutated_genes,   genes_informing_score,   gene_rank,   debug_mode = FALSE )

title: Generate score based on genes — score_based_on_gene_rank
text: mutated_genes vector genes mutated single sample (character) genes_informing_score genes determine sort order? (character) gene_rank order importance genes used determine sort order. Higher number = higher sort order (character) debug_mode debug mode (flag)

title: Generate score based on genes — score_based_on_gene_rank
text: score (higher = higher sorting order) (number)

title: Generate score based on genes — score_based_on_gene_rank
code: if (FALSE) { # First set of genes has a high rank since both BRCA2 and EGFR are mutated score_based_on_gene_rank(c("TERT", "EGFR", "PTEN", "BRCA2"), c("EGFR", "BRCA2"), gene_rank = 1:2)  # If EGFR is mutated without BRCA2, we get a lower score score_based_on_gene_rank(c("TERT", "EGFR", "PTEN", "IDH1"), c("EGFR", "BRCA2"), gene_rank = 1:2)  # If BRCA2 is mutated without EGFR, # we get a score lower than BRCA2+EGFR but higher than EGFR alone due to higher gene_rank of BRCA2 score_based_on_gene_rank(c("TERT", "IDH1", "PTEN", "BRCA2"), c("EGFR", "BRCA2"), gene_rank = 1:2) }
